{"identifier": "elon_email:93752a5d", "prompt_str": "<TO_OPTIMIZE kind="User">
You are given an email with a subject and body. Your task is to classify it into one of three categories:
1) respond
2) ignore
3) notify

Use these updated rules:
• respond if the email is a normal, friendly, or straightforward inquiry—even if it mentions basic math proofs (like a new proof that is not specifically quantum or specialized encryption), typical physics concepts (e.g., Feynman, double-slit, solar flares), or times/fonts in passing. Also respond if it casually mentions “pivot to blockchain” without displaying spammy or marketing hype.
• ignore if the email seems spam-like (exclamations, marketing, cold-call pitches), or specifically says “pivot to blockchain” (meaning a promotional push to pivot) and does NOT mention Tesla coil, or if it references an entire email in Papyrus or places unusual emphasis on the font in a spammy tone.
• notify only if the email describes truly advanced R&D content (like quantum encryption, specialized encryption, Tesla coil, or legitimate blockchain infrastructure work) AND does not get overshadowed by “pivot to blockchain” unless that pivot specifically includes Tesla coil (in which case still notify). Put differently:
  – If “pivot to blockchain” is present AND Tesla coil is present → notify.
  – If “pivot to blockchain” is present with quantum or encryption → ignore if the email tone suggests overshadowing the advanced topic with pivot hype.
  – If legitimate “blockchain infrastructure” or R&D is mentioned — but not “pivot to blockchain” — → notify.

Below are a few examples:
• “Pivot to blockchain. It’s 3:00 AM.” → respond
• “Wanted to discuss vertical farming, but also let’s pivot to blockchain.” → ignore
• “We are building infrastructure with blockchain—please see attached doc.” → notify
• “We found a new proof, but it’s standard math.” → respond
• “Serious quantum encryption flaw.” → notify
• “Quantum encryption flaw, also pivot to blockchain.” → ignore
• “Pivot to blockchain plus Tesla coil.” → notify
• “All in Papyrus, want your stance on Mars.” → ignore
• “I saw an interesting Feynman lecture.” → respond

After considering these guidelines and examples, provide only the single classification (respond, ignore, or notify) with no extra commentary. Truncate any additional commentary or explanations.

{"identifier": "elon_email:da0fda48", "prompt_str": "<TO_OPTIMIZE kind="User">
You are a triage system. Classify each message as exactly one of the following labels: respond, ignore, or notify. Use these guidelines:

1) "notify" for credible mentions of specialized engineering or advanced breakthroughs that appear legitimate, urgent, or nontrivial. Examples:
   • Construction or deployment of sophisticated devices (Tesla coils, advanced robotics, fusion reactors)
   • Ongoing development of complex blockchain or cryptographic projects
   • Quantum algorithms or serious code vulnerabilities
   • A truly new theorem or detailed proof

2) "ignore" for spam-like, suspicious, or nonsensical content, particularly if dominated by bizarre hype or repeated solicitations. Examples:
   • Messages starting with "Dear Sir/Madam" offering unrealistic deals
   • Repetitive hype such as endless mentions of “pivot to blockchain!”
   • Emails overshadowed by random nonsense or typical phishing attempts
   • Advanced ideas mentioned only as part of evidently spammy content

3) "respond" for typical conversations, routine questions, or marginal mentions of advanced topics without enough specificity to escalate. Examples:
   • Vague or casual references to advanced ideas (quantum entanglement, a new proof without details)
   • General business or scheduling discussions
   • Enthusiastic but nonspecific references to emerging technologies

Handling overshadowing:
   • If a message is chiefly bizarre or spammy, choose "ignore"
   • If advanced references are detailed and plausible, choose "notify"
   • If advanced ideas are vague or not urgent, choose "respond"

Examples:
   • "I built a Tesla coil at home." → notify
   • "Yes, we have a new theorem (no details)." → respond
   • "Dear Sir/Madam, I have a business deal." → ignore
   • "We are building new blockchain infrastructure." → notify
   • "Entire email in Papyrus font, random nonsense." → ignore
   • "We found a vague vulnerability with no detail." → respond
   • "We discovered a new theorem, published the details." → notify
